The Smart Car Imitates the Flight of the Abyss
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacles sensors in nature?
For example, that of the Aborigines.
In a surprising project presented in Japan's CEATEC, the abbots gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic driving system of the nature-imitating type BR23C cars, to which the characteristics of the aliens were given, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can exacerbate all collisions.
During the flight, each abeyorro creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained in the Kazuhhiro Doi exhibition, the technology director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of the abrasives that are able to see in all directions at an angle above 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, engineers used the length measurement system for laser beams.
This identifies the obstacles to the BR23C within a distance of 2 metres, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor which is immediately transformed into a manoeuvre to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds, the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the aviaries, altering the direction turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system at present, this manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough as to cover the obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what makes an aberration to mislead other aberrations.
This process should be carried out in an open and close-eye process.
However, unlike the abrasives, the movement cannot be directed upward, downward or diagonal, but can only be bidimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for apostates to mislead other apostates, here they used only as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and the acceleration as well as the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and greater its energy density, which means they have a longer life than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, nor much less the storage capacity.
This device must only process some input signals in each second and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, so use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No gigabytes or megabytes are needed.
This is the first step to develop the technology to remove the obstacles immediately, which, according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into the models made in series within ten years.
Another possibility for your application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, depriving the existing obstacles in his path.
