Jaróka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris, its host is France that this year is also President of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party by Fidesz, in his message addressed to the full, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, called attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that afflict Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights protection organizations attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of Members in the European Parliament - warned that, in addition to discrimination in employment, the Roma remain outside the labour market first because of their low level of education.
"Most of the young Roma have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a minor part can obtain university degree."
Jároka further stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a crucial role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Euro MP, there is a need to raise these issues widely between both the Roma and the non-Gitanians.
As early as the school starts, a gypsum student will have more opportunities to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gitanians, as citizens of the European Union, must guarantee them the right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the European Parliament, the European Union's objective and active unity is necessary to speed up the process of school dropout, which is essential for the proper implementation of existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"There is a need to break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, to offer Roma children the opportunity to guarantee democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full-right citizens," Járóka demanded.
The objective of the European Summit on Equal Opportunities organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting, which was held in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a single forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
