Goodbye to the old cinema Paradise, the cities cancel the historic halls
Historical cinematographic rooms close favoring the Multiplex.
"A city without cinematographic rooms in a blind city is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by Director Giuseppe Tornatore photographes effectively what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticians in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory," it is as if a friend died, a well-known person with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared," observes the director of the new film Paradise, the film that was twenty years ago won the first Oscar and the grand jury award to Cannes, who counted the poetry of a movie room in the province and the nostalgia in the way of living the film that was lost perhaps forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of traders, are clear: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and to pay most are mainly the rooms of the main cities: 10 minus in Florence, 9 minus in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 minus in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures are the first, Emilia-Romana with 82 smaller cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardia (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for his disappearance is the adventure of multiplex, these three Italian regions themselves that have recorded the largest number of new methic cinemas: 195 screens but in Lombardia in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romema.
“Italian exercise has been irrationally developed” notes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it would be useful for new structures to be built but it would be necessary to ensure that those already existing exist, because when a city hall closes, not all its members are willing to transfer to the mechanics.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately EUR 10 million.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To support the sector, between EUR 16 and 18 million per year would be used."
Interestingly to the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned by the closures, decided to repair itself with the signature of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the film mono room either in the historical center or in the periphery.
The proposed rules include means of tax facilitation in favour of managers and advantages to the public in terms of mobility: viewers can enter the restricted area of traffic and have special parking rates.
"It is an initiative that I like" notes Giuseppe Tornatore and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by introducing other measures.
It is true that in contrast to the extra power of mechanics, traditional rooms need to improve the quality of sound and image because today the public is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the movies in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to carry out the "New Paradise cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years now.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I move forward to the Rialto or the National Road Quirinale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the dusty posters, I turn to the other side.”
